segments.text: At that, as a junior faculty member, you were expecting to stay in higher education.
You weren't planning to...
There was not much opportunity outside of educational institutions for them to follow, because most of that was done at educational institutions.
there are a lot of commercial laboratories that do research even now do that a lot of it and there are some contract laboratories and they they do this.
Now when did you first remember getting acquainted with Alvin Price?
Alvin Price was an assistant professor in anatomy.
Of course, he graduated after I left, and it was only after I came back here that I met him.
But even in anatomy, my relationships were with, at that time then, were with John Milliff.
And I guess when he became dean, I became cognizant that he was there.
When did he become dean?
I could look that up for you.
Because I think he was dean when I got here in 59.
That could be.
You better pray quickly, honey, so he doesn't hear you.
No, no, that's all right.
No.
I don't remember either one.
But I said, now he's one that would be a wonderful person to interview.
Oh, see, that's what I regret, yes.
Because he could have given you lots of information.
Now, is he bedridden totally?
No, he sits up in a chair.
Okay.
But he doesn't.
That's what I understand.
Al Price became dean in 1957 after Armistead departed.
Do you recall that you all felt good about his appointment as dean?
Very much so.
Describe his style of leadership.
was mature for his age, in my opinion.
And of course, I think part of that, he had, and I think Earl Rutter picked him.
And Al had been an infantry officer in World War II, Colonel.
And he had some of that value, but he had a very congenial way of working with you.
and letting you know he wanted something done.
He said, here's your job, let's see it done.

And I remember one time I had an animal laboratory above his office and the students would get too much water down there and it would come through on him and he got a hold of me and he says, you stop that.
If you don't, I'm going to take care of it.
But he was very, as you say, a very capable manager and a leader.
And so you all respected him highly?
I did, yes.
And I think everybody did.
When did the vet school move west of the tracks?
Was it about the time he became dean?
1958, I believe.
Okay.
Did you faculty members get to have any part in planning the new facilities?
Yes.
I got together the information department, and I had the incinerator and what they just found out, a duct made 5 billion dollars to build a new one.
Then we designed the whole second floor of the medical building, the other one for the science.
I thought we designed the whole second floor of that for our laboratories and operations.
And of course, we had the architect change some of our design.
Were you all pleased with those facilities?
Oh, very much so.
others were jealous of them and we were just fortunate that we needed space.
We had a very strong program at that time.
Would nationally the program in pathology was becoming known?
Very much so.
Yeah, I think we were one of the top programs.
Who were the other among the top programs at that time?
Cornell had
historically has had an excellent program.
And Washington State at that time had a strong program for research.
And Michigan also had a good, strong program.
The others I think were respectable, but I thought we had probably one of the better ones we had.
When I, my last year
I think we had 15 or 16 Ph.D. students when veterinary medicine was pretty strong, surely.
Now, when you all first moved over there, late 50s, what were the other strong programs in veterinary medicine other than pathology?
I think microbiology had a strong program.
They had not developed their Ph.D. program.
And as I remember, we were about the only one that had anything of any strength at that time.
Those all came on later.
Who were the most highly respected faculty members in the other departments?
You're talking about other than department heads?
Yeah.
Who would have been known nationally?
Oh, I see what you mean.
Well, the people in microbiology were known primarily for their disease programs.
Who were they?
Charles Hall, and there were others that were through there, but those two name was there, I think.
John Dell played before that.
John Leland succeeded him after he died.
And what about any of the other departments, nationally known scholars?
Well, Millet, honey, from anatomy was pretty well known, wasn't he?
Millet was known, but he was known as a teacher, as a pathologist.
But in our practice, he was a grandfathered into the American College of Endopathy.
But they didn't have a graduate program.

as you look back now on the veterinary medicine medical curriculum at that time were there any things that were getting too much attention and were there any topics getting too little attention in the veterinary curriculum at that time as we know that's a matter of opinion and uh i felt uh very strongly
Yes, I do, even in primary education today, that there are certain things that are most important, reading and writing.
Okay.
And in medicine, I think that the anatomy, pathology, and physiology are the foundations.
Okay.
Which are on basis for everything else.
And I think that when you decide what you're going to study, both diseases and rat diseases and
and do all these, you divide the person's attention, which they cannot do.
However, the human mind has strengths that can overcome this.
I think, yes, I think that the students are overwhelmed.
And some of the Canadian schools recognize this, and they were strong in basics.
And in fact, they were stronger in basics in a lot of their clinical
efforts were not, well they figured they could learn that.
That's an applications type thing.
What that's again is a matter of opinion.
If you're teaching public health, and veterinarians are very heavy now in public health, and advisories and things like that, that person is going to say well that's important.

in the late 50s early 60s among the students in veterinary medicine how many of them hope to be in large animal what percentage or small animal what was the breakdown then well i think in those days uh there i i would hesitate to say i would say at least 50 50. okay now they're there i i think this could be documented
But I don't have those pictures.
Were there many who were looking primarily toward public health in that era?
Not many, no.
A lot of them got into public health because if they had a service obligation, they would go into veterinary training programs and services would send them to public health schools.
A lot of them went to Tulane or places like that.
and out of the service because the service wouldn't allow them to do those things.
You became department head when?
All right.
As you become department head, what did you find were the primary responsibilities of being a department head?
Well, it was the direction of the program and basically is defining people to do the work.
and that was a problem at that time because when Hilton left there was not a heavy component of strong pathology there.
I mean the people that had advanced training
And the level that I was concerned that it should have been a university level for people to teach others.
How many PhDs were in the department then?
You were the only one?
And the faculty was how many?
I think four or five.
And did Dean Price, when he appointed you, did he give you any instructions, any guidance, any directions?
I don't remember that he dictated anything.
He said, he expressed that he wanted to see it develop, and he said, can I help?
And I think he respected the program and the needs, and I don't remember anything
Now you served how many years?
As you were starting out, did you turn to any of the other department heads for advice?
Don't remember any of them doing so.
I've had discussions, but if you know men, men will get information by not asking us what should I do.
Who became your closest friends?
One of the closest relationships was where there was a parallel, say, a friendship because we hunted together.
It was J.D.
McCready.
And part of that I saw myself because I was trying to develop research programs.
And the big thing then was collaborative, which works fine to a certain extent.
But some people don't want to collaborate.
A lot of them look at a pathologist being like, can you read this slide for me and tell me what it is and I'll report it.
And some of that is that, but there are others that work with us.
So we would seek out those kinds of things and try to work them out.
Make believe that I was not acquainted with this man McCready.
Describe him.
What was his specialty, and what was his normal operating procedure?
He was a very extroverted person.
And as I see him, and very capable of being a good politician, and friendly to most anybody.
And he had a lot of good contacts because of his association with the medical school at Baylor.
And his department?
Physiology.
He was supposed to be in physiology.
And he had some very good people with him.
And he had a very large program because they taught a lot of students.
Was he department head when you became department head?
No.
When I became department head, I was a junior person, and I perceived that I was thought to be so.
Did you department heads meet regularly with Dean Price?
Yes, he had department meetings.
Describe one of those.
What was a typical meeting like?
Well, I don't know how to say that.
They would, he would basically have an agenda.
He would call, you know, have a meeting to order and he would present things to be looked at and he would start a discussion.
And from that, ordinarily, he would make a decision.
Occasionally, he would ask for a vote, which I thought was not a very smart thing to do.
That's just a bunch of opinions.
Was he always bound by the majority vote?
No, I don't think so, in my opinion.
I don't think he was.
I think he did his own, you know, made up his own mind.
Yeah, he was pretty smart, too.
But did you ever feel that it was to your disadvantage not to be candid with him?
I don't think I'd not want to be candid with him.
That's what I thought.
That's the answer I thought.
He didn't mind telling me what he thought, but he was also always very polite.
It's just amazing.
Among the other department heads, who were your favorite associates?
I would say that there were not any such thing except the Leland drum, which now went back a long ways.
He and I were reared that five miles each time.
And among the department heads, seven, eight?
I think it was seven most of the time.
And when you became a department head, was there anyone who was the senior senior?
that had been there a long, long time?
Well, of course, Pat Burns had been there longer than anybody.
Okay.
But Pat Burns was a very quiet individual and soft-spoken and not outspoken.
Dick Turk was probably the most outgoing and you might say influential type of person because of his
He let his opinion be known.
As department head, what was your style within your department?
Did you have faculty meetings regularly?
We had faculty meetings, and we would discuss things, and seldom did I ask for a vote.
I asked for opinions.
Because I found that if you ask somebody's opinion and you don't respect it, then you begin to erode your support.
And you have to maintain your support for them by individual discussions.
That's my opinion.
I guess I'm old school.
Do you remember any examples of where your opinion and what you thought was the majority of the department's opinion were different?
Can you think of any?
Nothing comes to mind right now.
What were some of the most important decisions that you and the department made during all the years you were department head?
That's very hard to answer.

We had a program where I tried to get over to each individual faculty member, do your best, develop something, become known, remember that you, the department's going to be made up with you and your colleagues, and his reputation will be based on the community, and then I'll support, I'll try to help you.
I had to make decisions that they didn't like, reassigning the laboratories and things like that.
I had one in tears one time, but he's now a dean of the Air Corps in Connecticut, I believe it is.
And those things like that, I guess that
I was the decision-maker.
And were you the key person in selecting new faculty for the department?
Yes.
Who are some of the faculty you're proud that you hire?
Well, Ken Pierce was a very capable individual.
Make believe I don't know him, and tell me about him.
a very serious, quiet, no funny business type of person that is very professional.
He...
I would like people in categories and several of the faculty that I could put into categories.
Some of the people are so introverted that they never get anything done.
So many people are so extroverted they never get anything done.
and the people that make progress are in between.
Ken was just a little bit on the middle, below the middle.
He was more introverted, but he was very safe.
Quality of his work was so good.
Where did you first kind of identify him?
Where did you?
Well, in the days when Ken came, we were trying to build a power.
And he was one of the first that came in.
He had been teaching on anatomy.
And he'd gone out and said he needed to do some practice.
So he went out and he wanted to come back.
So I interviewed him for an opportunity in pathology.
Did he contact you or you contact him?
I don't remember exactly how that came.
I think I did not know without his.
his innocent pathology.
I think, basically, it may be that Hilton had somewhere had some contact with him.
Because wouldn't he have been among the first faculty you hired?
Yes.
He would have been one of the strengths.
Did he do his doctoral degree here?
Yes.
With you?
Yes.
I was his major professor.
You were his chairman?
I'll tell you a story that I don't really know.
But I did him wrong.
You don't want it on tape?
No.
Let's turn this back on now.
A few things about leadership.
You want people to want to do what you want done.
And this is the essence of it.
And this is what's happening in this area that you're talking about.
People are going out with joyous things.
And that's the thing where the big congregations are very developing.
that's what they're doing.
They're not depending on, you ought to do this.
That's right.
Kind of the thing of the old groups.
How did you encourage that philosophy in the department?
Well, we had a, there is a strong, there was a strong spirit of code in the department, and we felt like we
And I always told them that you should know as much about veterinary medicine and diseases as anybody, even including the clinicians, except that you don't have to mess with the clients.
And you are supposed to be academically, or you're supposed to have the answers to know and be able to solve problems.
And people should come to you and you should be prepared
that he would come to you for answers, which people want to do, a pathologist.
They say, well, here, I've got a problem.
Help me.
Tell me about it.
And we developed a very strong disparity core.
And there is a very strong certifying group of American College of Endocrine Pathologists.
And people know that they need to aspire to pass their exams.
and the county would have been dependent upon each other to learn.
And we were proud of our department, and I'm a little concerned that that's been hurt a little bit by the amalgamation of the groups and taken out of the way.
For example, they no longer have parties together as individuals, and people want to be identified.
They, like the cadets, their companies are the sole, their sole arrangement.
And then... All right, as department head, did you all have social events as a department?
We'd have people... Quite a few.
Ken continued that at some.
And later others came in that dropped in.

i think it is hurt a while ago we were talking and you were saying ken you were proud to have brought him here are there some others that you want to mention well there's one right now that is jewel and that's gary adams gary adams and he told me yesterday he's been he's been over promotion but he doesn't know where he wants to accept did you now did you bring him here
He was my graduate student.
Oh, your graduate student, okay.
And then he stayed.
And he stayed, yeah.
During your time as department head, were there any major research efforts in which the department was involved that you're proud to claim that they all were part of it?
We were participating in a lot of research programs.
And we had our own, and each individual had programs that many of them were sponsored by the National Institutes of Health.
I had, I was program director of a public health, a U.S. public health, National Institutes of Health Training and Medical Pathology, which was well respected.
And that went for 10 years until we finally phased those programs out.
We did,
research on quite a few things and try to solve problems.

The some others in collaboration with others, I tell told somebody, and now in my age in my position, I tell them if you want to see anything, the impact, the impact of our research, I said you go to now to Lexington, Kentucky, you'll see that the all the board fences are painted black.
And the essence of that was the research that I did to find that the young foals were licking the fences and getting zinc from that.
From the white paint.
From the white paint.
And that inhibited the absorption of copper, which they were getting very little from milk to start with.
And the joints fell apart.
peeled off, the carcass peeled off.
Did that affect the thoroughbred horses more than any other breeds?
Mainly because thoroughbred horses were the horses that were kept in the fancy fences.
Oh, in the fancy fences.
The Kleberg Foundation funded this.
Bubba Wattuck told me not too long ago, he said, that building ought to be named for you
She said, they sponsored that because of your work.
And so I feel good about that, and we did.
Other examples like that?
We worked on... What was that grass business, honey?
We worked on, yeah, there's a photosynthesization that occurs with panicum grass.
It's just planted commercially, I mean, intentionally.
particularly for sheep, they're grazing that.
And they develop this, eat this panicament.
Sometimes they do, sometimes they don't.
But the young lambs particularly develop photosensitization, which really results from their liver being damaged by crystals of this saponin.
The saponin is a common component of plants.
This stuff precipitates in there, and it has a chemical structure very similar to cholesterol.
And the liver, because it is an analog of cholesterol, the liver handles it to a certain point, and then it precipitates in the bile ducts.
And that plugs them up, and then they retain the porphyrins, which come from plants also, circulates through the blood, and into the skin, and the sun gets on that and activates it.
and it caused their skin to slow.
And we worked that out to find out why this particular plant is.
Of course, nothing has happened from that other than they could either plant the stuff or not plant it.

There was a chance for them to, if they wanted, if it was important enough that somebody could take the plant and develop some that had less saponins or do find out when sheep would be more successful.
There are things like that that we did, and that is to work on identifying mycotic diseases of horses particularly and others that are unique diseases.
Did y'all ever do anything...
